# HandLayout.elm — TINY

Pinned hand layout. `View.viewHand` iterates the hand, computes
`{ row, col }` for each card, and calls `positionAt` to place
its DOM node. That's the only job.

## Why pinned

The hand always renders at a known position derived from layout
constants — suit-row index + within-row index. No CSS flex, no
late layout decisions. This keeps the renderer total (no
`Maybe`) and the visual stable.

## Key exports

- `positionAt : { row, col } -> { x, y }` — viewport center of
  a grid cell. Used by the renderer.
- `handLeft`, `handTop`, `suitRowHeight` — layout constants.
- `handCardDomId : Card -> String` — stable DOM id. Used by
  the replay synthesizer with `Browser.Dom.getElement` to
  fetch a hand card's LIVE viewport rect (disambiguates
  double-deck copies via the originDeck suffix).

## The DOM is authoritative at replay time

Earlier versions carried a `cardCenterInViewport` that
computed a card's viewport center from pinned math. After the
"landing right, origin wrong" bug (2026-04-21), the replay
synthesis pipeline was switched to live DOM measurement via
`handCardDomId`. `cardCenterInViewport` and its helper
`suitRowIndex` had zero remaining callers and were ripped.

### Rule for future edits

Do not synthesize a hand-card's viewport position from the
constants here. Any viewport coord consumed by the replay
drag floater must come from a DOM measurement. See
`Main.claude` and `Main/Replay/Space.claude` for the general
rule and the pattern to follow when extending synthesis.

## Pointers

- Complement: `BoardGeometry.boardViewportLeft` / `Top` pin
  the board; the two modules together pin the whole playable
  area for the renderer.
- Consumer (render): `LynRummy.View.viewHand`.
- Consumer (DOM id only): `Main.Replay.Time.prepareReplayStep`.

## TODO

- Constants (`handLeft`, `handTop`, `suitRowHeight`) are
  hardcoded for the current layout. If the top bar / status
  bar heights change, update them. No preflight check yet
  that they stay consistent with the Elm page layout around
  them.
